00:01:31.740 --> 00:01:33.045
engine as well as yourself.

00:01:35.830 --> 00:01:39.510
So there are really three
parts to this presentation.

00:01:39.510 --> 00:01:43.260
We're going to talk about
some basic sleep science.

00:01:43.260 --> 00:01:46.470
Then I'm going to get into
the most common challenges

00:01:46.470 --> 00:01:48.480
and problems parents
find with their child

00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:53.080
and sleep and then
talk about solutions.

00:01:53.080 --> 00:01:57.570
So in terms of common myths,
the most popular common myths

00:01:57.570 --> 00:02:00.660
I confront in my
work are that babies

00:02:00.660 --> 00:02:04.000
will sleep when they are
12 pounds and 12 weeks.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:04.840
Wrong.

00:02:04.840 --> 00:02:08.130
There is no medical
research to back that up.

00:02:08.130 --> 00:02:10.199
Number two, babies will
sleep through the night

00:02:10.199 --> 00:02:12.360
when they start solids.

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:14.280
Wrong again.

00:02:14.280 --> 00:02:20.200
Food does not have anything to
do with sleep or sleeping well.

00:02:20.200 --> 00:02:23.490
And third, if you put
your baby to sleep late,

00:02:23.490 --> 00:02:27.730
they will sleep long and
longer in the morning,

00:02:27.730 --> 00:02:28.740
which is the key there.

00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:31.590
That is also false,
unfortunately.

00:02:31.590 --> 00:02:36.490
And we'll talk about
why that is the case.

00:02:36.490 --> 00:02:38.140
If there's only
one thing that you

00:02:38.140 --> 00:02:41.830
will remember from
this talk, I want you

00:02:41.830 --> 00:02:44.020
to remember this at all times.

00:02:44.020 --> 00:02:48.930
That sleep is actually
a learned skill.

00:02:48.930 --> 00:02:51.270
Some babies will
simply find it easier,

00:02:51.270 --> 00:02:53.690
and others will find
it more challenging.

00:02:53.690 --> 00:02:57.210
And there's a number
of reasons that is.

00:02:57.210 --> 00:02:58.950
But it's always
important to remember

00:02:58.950 --> 00:03:02.880
that it's a learned
skill just like crawling,

00:03:02.880 --> 00:03:04.262
walking, talking.

00:03:04.262 --> 00:03:05.595
All of those are learned skills.

00:03:08.510 --> 00:03:12.230
Secondly, sleep is a
neurological development.

00:03:12.230 --> 00:03:16.730
And most babies are ready to
sleep through the night, as we

00:03:16.730 --> 00:03:20.230
say, around six months.

00:03:20.230 --> 00:03:24.040
And we'll get into the
details of that in a minute.

00:03:24.040 --> 00:03:26.380
And lastly on the slide,
I want to highlight

00:03:26.380 --> 00:03:28.810
that there's great
variability about when

00:03:28.810 --> 00:03:31.690
babies are ready to
sleep through the night.

00:03:31.690 --> 00:03:35.110
And I say that because there's
so much information out

00:03:35.110 --> 00:03:38.770
there and so many books that
promise parents things that

00:03:38.770 --> 00:03:43.250
are simply the case for maybe
20% or 30% of the population.

00:03:43.250 --> 00:03:46.150
But if you're in 70% to
80% of the population,

00:03:46.150 --> 00:03:48.370
it doesn't really
matter, does it?

00:03:48.370 --> 00:03:50.830
So I always highlight
that variability

00:03:50.830 --> 00:03:54.904
because some babies
may be ready to do

00:03:54.904 --> 00:03:57.070
that sleeping through the
night earlier than others,

00:03:57.070 --> 00:03:58.060
and some later.

00:03:58.060 --> 00:03:58.910
And that's OK.

00:04:02.620 --> 00:04:05.560
So in terms of talking
about sleep science,

00:04:05.560 --> 00:04:08.020
technically, there is no
sleeping through the night.

00:04:08.020 --> 00:04:10.091
Now if you're a parent
who has a sleep challenge,

00:04:10.091 --> 00:04:11.590
you're probably
going, you're right.

00:04:11.590 --> 00:04:13.214
There is no sleeping
through the night.

00:04:13.214 --> 00:04:16.220
I haven't gotten
to that point yet.

00:04:16.220 --> 00:04:18.490
But I say this
because it's actually

00:04:18.490 --> 00:04:22.840
normal for every person to
have several night wakings.

00:04:22.840 --> 00:04:24.130
That's a brain function.

00:04:24.130 --> 00:04:26.260
Everybody wakes up
several times a night.

00:04:26.260 --> 00:04:30.520
The issue is if you know how
to put yourself to sleep,

00:04:30.520 --> 00:04:35.260
you can do it all
night long, as it were.

00:04:35.260 --> 00:04:37.830
On a completely
neurological level--

00:04:37.830 --> 00:04:40.290
and I'm simplifying this
for today's purpose--

00:04:40.290 --> 00:04:42.540
we have two kinds of sleep.

00:04:42.540 --> 00:04:46.830
We have deep sleep
and active sleep.

00:04:46.830 --> 00:04:51.840
We begin our night sleep going
into non-REM sleep, which is

00:04:51.840 --> 00:04:54.120
our deepest stretch of sleep.

00:04:54.120 --> 00:04:55.990
And then in the
middle of the night--

00:04:55.990 --> 00:04:57.870
and when I say
middle of the night,

00:04:57.870 --> 00:05:01.740
that means sometime between,
let's say, 12:00 and 3:00 AM--

00:05:01.740 --> 00:05:04.440
we shift gears very
much like a car

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:06.450
and go into active
and light sleep.

00:05:09.770 --> 00:05:12.860
And lastly, in terms of
the science piece of this,

00:05:12.860 --> 00:05:16.880
I want to highlight, again,
there is no scientific proof

00:05:16.880 --> 00:05:20.690
that food will help your
baby sleep better or well.

00:05:20.690 --> 00:05:24.650
And that doesn't mean we're
talking about milk or solids.

00:05:24.650 --> 00:05:28.400
Again, thinking about sleep
as a neurological development,

00:05:28.400 --> 00:05:32.660
a brain development
that goes on a fairly

00:05:32.660 --> 00:05:36.670
consistent and structured path
is important to keep in mind.

00:05:40.780 --> 00:05:41.680
Common issues.

00:05:41.680 --> 00:05:43.130
You are not alone.

00:05:43.130 --> 00:05:46.090
So I would say the
things that I tend

00:05:46.090 --> 00:05:50.950
to help parents with the
most are the following.

00:05:50.950 --> 00:05:55.360
My baby goes to sleep very
easily, but wakes several times

00:05:55.360 --> 00:05:56.050
a night.

00:05:56.050 --> 00:05:56.550
Right?

00:05:56.550 --> 00:05:59.920
So dealing with night
wakings, very common.

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:02.980
My baby needs to be
nursed or rocked or fed

00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:05.490
to sleep all night long.

00:06:05.490 --> 00:06:08.680
Again, several times a night.

00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:12.040
I hear very often from
parents, particularly babies

00:06:12.040 --> 00:06:14.590
under six months,
my baby will only

00:06:14.590 --> 00:06:18.330
sleep being held or co-sleeping.

00:06:18.330 --> 00:06:21.630
And then lastly,
my baby won't nap.

00:06:21.630 --> 00:06:24.610
Naps can be very challenging
for many children,

00:06:24.610 --> 00:06:28.830
particularly after a certain
age because of development

00:06:28.830 --> 00:06:32.320
for a variety of reasons.

00:06:32.320 --> 00:06:34.290
So what's normal, right?

00:06:34.290 --> 00:06:36.810
Because that's really important
to understand, particularly

00:06:36.810 --> 00:06:38.800
when you've got your next
door neighbor saying,

00:06:38.800 --> 00:06:40.980
well, my kid's been
sleeping through the night

00:06:40.980 --> 00:06:42.460
for the past several months.

00:06:42.460 --> 00:06:44.680
I don't know what's
going on with you.

00:06:44.680 --> 00:06:49.230
But it's very important to
understand what is normal.

00:06:49.230 --> 00:06:52.780
The age of the baby is really
important to keep in mind.

00:06:52.780 --> 00:06:57.000
So developmental age is very
important in respect to sleep.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:00.670
And whether the baby was
born pre-term, right?

00:07:00.670 --> 00:07:06.330
So before 40 weeks or
early, because sleep

00:07:06.330 --> 00:07:10.860
definitely goes on a
development after 40 weeks.

00:07:10.860 --> 00:07:13.170
So if your baby
was born pre-term,

00:07:13.170 --> 00:07:15.006
even if it's only
a few weeks, it's

00:07:15.006 --> 00:07:16.130
not that there's a problem.

00:07:16.130 --> 00:07:19.710
It's that they simply may not
get to certain development

00:07:19.710 --> 00:07:25.470
sleep wise until they
hit different milestones.

00:07:25.470 --> 00:07:28.740
Are there any medical
conditions, right?

00:07:28.740 --> 00:07:30.810
So the most common
medical conditions

00:07:30.810 --> 00:07:35.630
that tend to stand in the way
of sleep are things like reflux,

00:07:35.630 --> 00:07:41.600
or GERD, any ENT difficulties,
such as enlarged adenoids

00:07:41.600 --> 00:07:46.100
or tonsils, any type of
breathing difficulty.

00:07:46.100 --> 00:07:49.400
Is there a family
history of any of this?

00:07:49.400 --> 00:07:54.440
And then lastly, also
anemia, low iron stores

00:07:54.440 --> 00:07:57.110
can disturb sleep.

00:07:57.110 --> 00:07:59.600
So all of those things are
very important to keep in mind

00:07:59.600 --> 00:08:03.380
if you are confronting a sleep
challenge with your child.

00:08:03.380 --> 00:08:08.090
And in terms of young babies,
I want to highlight that babies

00:08:08.090 --> 00:08:09.700
under five months--

00:08:09.700 --> 00:08:10.700
OK?

00:08:10.700 --> 00:08:13.370
Feeding is more
important than sleeping.

00:08:13.370 --> 00:08:16.130
And the reason I say that
is because, again, there's

00:08:16.130 --> 00:08:17.900
a lot of information
out there that says,

00:08:17.900 --> 00:08:23.540
well, by 12 pounds in
12 weeks, your baby

00:08:23.540 --> 00:08:25.580
doesn't need to eat at night.

00:08:25.580 --> 00:08:26.750
Some may not.

00:08:26.750 --> 00:08:30.910
I would say the vast majority
still may need to eat at night.

00:08:30.910 --> 00:08:33.260
And so feeding
really comes first

00:08:33.260 --> 00:08:38.419
for those first four to five
months in my estimation.

00:08:38.419 --> 00:08:40.710
We need to make sure that
that's going perfectly.

00:08:40.710 --> 00:08:42.799
And if it's not for some
reason, we definitely

00:08:42.799 --> 00:08:47.210
want to have parents talk
to their pediatrician

00:08:47.210 --> 00:08:50.480
and/or a lactation consultant
to rule out any type of feeding

00:08:50.480 --> 00:08:51.570
difficulty for the child.

00:08:55.400 --> 00:08:57.800
Again, think about
what's normal.

00:08:57.800 --> 00:08:59.720
The American Academy
of Pediatrics

00:08:59.720 --> 00:09:01.610
states that babies
under six months

00:09:01.610 --> 00:09:04.860
may not have regular
sleep patterns.

00:09:04.860 --> 00:09:07.890
Now, many will present
regular sleep patterns,

00:09:07.890 --> 00:09:11.750
but this gives you the idea that
there's a big range of normal.

00:09:11.750 --> 00:09:13.920
And that's OK.

00:09:13.920 --> 00:09:15.710
And in terms of
the AAP guidelines

00:09:15.710 --> 00:09:20.270
in terms of how much your
child needs on a daily basis,

00:09:20.270 --> 00:09:22.400
they recently reviewed
them about two years ago

00:09:22.400 --> 00:09:26.810
and put out new guidelines
in terms of averages,

00:09:26.810 --> 00:09:31.730
about 17 to 14 hours a day
for babies under 12 months.

00:09:31.730 --> 00:09:33.590
Now, it's important
to keep in mind

00:09:33.590 --> 00:09:35.930
that in these first
few months, babies

00:09:35.930 --> 00:09:38.510
are going to sleep
short stretches

00:09:38.510 --> 00:09:40.640
and be awake short stretches.

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:44.055
So those first few months, we're
talking about short windows.

00:09:47.650 --> 00:09:49.990
So again, to go over
sleeping through the night,

00:09:49.990 --> 00:09:52.960
because that tends to be
what most of us as parents

00:09:52.960 --> 00:09:55.820
are looking for.

00:09:55.820 --> 00:09:58.520
To say again, there is no
sleeping through the night,

00:09:58.520 --> 00:10:02.330
but children need to
understand and remember

00:10:02.330 --> 00:10:05.750
how they fall asleep because
that is the skill we're

00:10:05.750 --> 00:10:09.650
looking for all night long.

00:10:09.650 --> 00:10:12.630
And then of course
later for naps as well.

00:10:12.630 --> 00:10:15.740
And so the way a baby knows
how to fall asleep at bedtime

00:10:15.740 --> 00:10:17.960
becomes the foundation
of what they're going

00:10:17.960 --> 00:10:22.690
to look for all night long.

00:10:22.690 --> 00:10:31.460
So to highlight one problem that
many parents face, and I just

00:10:31.460 --> 00:10:36.000
like to tease out a little
bit, I talked to many parents,

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:39.080
particularly at this time
of year or in May who say,

00:10:39.080 --> 00:10:41.660
my child wakes up every
single day at 5 AM.

00:10:41.660 --> 00:10:44.900
Now, of course, with sunrise
so early this time of year,

00:10:44.900 --> 00:10:48.710
that can be due to too much
light in the child's room

00:10:48.710 --> 00:10:49.721
too early.

00:10:49.721 --> 00:10:51.970
But I'd like to highlight
the difference between night

00:10:51.970 --> 00:10:56.570
wakings and early rising because
many children tend to get up

00:10:56.570 --> 00:10:58.430
very early in the morning.

00:10:58.430 --> 00:11:02.510
And so night wakings happen
any time after bedtime

00:11:02.510 --> 00:11:08.090
and are usually due to too late
of a bed time, the baby being

00:11:08.090 --> 00:11:16.320
put to bed asleep already,
and also nap deprivation.

00:11:16.320 --> 00:11:21.200
So either naps that are too
short or just poorly timed

00:11:21.200 --> 00:11:23.450
can cause night wakings.

00:11:23.450 --> 00:11:25.520
Now, in terms of early rising--

00:11:25.520 --> 00:11:29.600
which I define as waking
consistently at 5:00

00:11:29.600 --> 00:11:33.170
AM or really any time
in that, let's say, 4:30

00:11:33.170 --> 00:11:36.110
to before 6:00 AM time--

00:11:36.110 --> 00:11:39.020
that also usually
happens because bedtime

00:11:39.020 --> 00:11:44.720
is too late, because
of nap deprivation,

00:11:44.720 --> 00:11:46.590
and/or a medical condition.

00:11:46.590 --> 00:11:48.450
So there are certain
medical conditions,

00:11:48.450 --> 00:11:50.960
particularly the
breathing difficulties,

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:54.330
that can cause early rising.

00:11:54.330 --> 00:11:56.510
So I just like to highlight
the differences there

00:11:56.510 --> 00:12:01.280
because they can be
different although similarly

00:12:01.280 --> 00:12:03.990
related problems.

00:12:03.990 --> 00:12:04.990
Naps.

00:12:04.990 --> 00:12:10.930
So naps are really important
for children basically three

00:12:10.930 --> 00:12:12.000
years and under.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.400
And it's really chicken
and egg in the sense

00:12:14.400 --> 00:12:21.970
that nighttime sleep affects
daytime sleep, and vise versa.

00:12:21.970 --> 00:12:25.110
So many times, naps
will not be great

00:12:25.110 --> 00:12:27.870
until nighttime
sleep gets better.

00:12:27.870 --> 00:12:31.710
But conversely, naps
may not be great

00:12:31.710 --> 00:12:34.810
because nighttime
sleep is a problem.

00:12:34.810 --> 00:12:38.570
So in many ways, bedtime
is the foundation

00:12:38.570 --> 00:12:42.480
of how your child
understands to sleep.

00:12:42.480 --> 00:12:46.170
We then build on it with
proper nighttime sleep,

00:12:46.170 --> 00:12:50.550
and then naps will usually
fall into place last.

00:12:50.550 --> 00:12:54.600
And so I like to highlight that
as well because many people

00:12:54.600 --> 00:12:57.720
have questions with their
children in terms of naps

00:12:57.720 --> 00:12:59.880
because they change
so much from,

00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:06.250
let's say, 6 months to 12
months to 18 months to beyond.

00:13:06.250 --> 00:13:09.930
And in terms of when
children will stop napping,

00:13:09.930 --> 00:13:13.290
it tends to be sometime between
the third and fourth year

00:13:13.290 --> 00:13:13.800
of life.

00:13:16.750 --> 00:13:21.940
So now, talking about solutions.

00:13:21.940 --> 00:13:25.020
One of the most important
things I talk to parents about

00:13:25.020 --> 00:13:27.390
is crib acclimatization.

00:13:27.390 --> 00:13:31.020
And what that means
is your child really

00:13:31.020 --> 00:13:35.400
needs to understand where
you expect them to sleep.

00:13:35.400 --> 00:13:39.180
So imagine last night,
you went to bed.

00:13:39.180 --> 00:13:41.760
And you distinctly remember
the washing up process,

00:13:41.760 --> 00:13:44.550
or taking a shower, or getting
into bed thinking, oh God.

00:13:44.550 --> 00:13:45.810
Thank goodness.

00:13:45.810 --> 00:13:48.390
And then you find
yourself waking up

00:13:48.390 --> 00:13:50.800
in the middle of
your kitchen floor.

00:13:50.800 --> 00:13:54.160
And you think, wait, no, it was
not a crazy, wonderful night

00:13:54.160 --> 00:13:54.681
last night.

00:13:54.681 --> 00:13:55.930
This should not have happened.

00:13:55.930 --> 00:13:57.490
How did I end up here?

00:13:57.490 --> 00:14:01.510
And that sort of
out-of-body experience

00:14:01.510 --> 00:14:06.010
I don't know who moved me is
what your child will experience

00:14:06.010 --> 00:14:08.600
when they are transferred.

00:14:08.600 --> 00:14:12.670
And at some age, that transfer
tends to stop working.

00:14:12.670 --> 00:14:14.110
Now what does that mean?

00:14:14.110 --> 00:14:16.900
I put my baby to
sleep here in my arms.

00:14:16.900 --> 00:14:18.670
It's all wonderful and cozy.

00:14:18.670 --> 00:14:22.860
I transfer him into the crib.

00:14:22.860 --> 00:14:24.720
But then he wakes
up two hours later

00:14:24.720 --> 00:14:28.350
and is screaming bloody murder,
and I'm not really sure why.

00:14:28.350 --> 00:14:30.900
Well, one of the reasons
is because he doesn't

00:14:30.900 --> 00:14:33.360
remember getting into the crib.

00:14:33.360 --> 00:14:35.280
So that's really important.

00:14:35.280 --> 00:14:38.670
So making sure that your
child spend some time

00:14:38.670 --> 00:14:40.610
during the day--

00:14:40.610 --> 00:14:43.750
I usually suggest few
minutes in the morning,

00:14:43.750 --> 00:14:47.350
a few minutes in the
afternoon while they're awake.

00:14:47.350 --> 00:14:51.700
Chilling out, relaxing, hanging
out in their sleep space

00:14:51.700 --> 00:14:54.670
so that it is not
a surprise to them

00:14:54.670 --> 00:15:00.800
when they are asked to go to
sleep in that place later on.

00:15:00.800 --> 00:15:05.810
And if you heard me say go to
sleep in that place later on,

00:15:05.810 --> 00:15:10.850
ultimately, we want our children
to go to sleep in their crib.

00:15:10.850 --> 00:15:14.120
Not in our arms, not
bouncing on a ball,

00:15:14.120 --> 00:15:16.220
not being held,
because we want them

00:15:16.220 --> 00:15:20.810
to experience falling asleep
where they should stay asleep.

00:15:20.810 --> 00:15:22.970
So getting them used
to their sleep space,

00:15:22.970 --> 00:15:27.020
acclimating them a little bit
each day is really important.

00:15:27.020 --> 00:15:29.330
I usually suggest
this as a first step

00:15:29.330 --> 00:15:31.520
in getting out of any
kind of sleep challenge

00:15:31.520 --> 00:15:34.180
with your child.

00:15:34.180 --> 00:15:36.340
Next.

00:15:36.340 --> 00:15:40.090
Again, in terms of
when a young baby is

00:15:40.090 --> 00:15:42.130
ready to sleep
through the night,

00:15:42.130 --> 00:15:43.930
that baby is eating
every three or four

00:15:43.930 --> 00:15:45.640
hours throughout a night.

00:15:45.640 --> 00:15:49.696
Well, that's not
going to happen if--

00:15:49.696 --> 00:15:51.070
sleeping through
the night is not

00:15:51.070 --> 00:15:52.820
going to happen obviously
if they're still

00:15:52.820 --> 00:15:54.140
eating very frequently.

00:15:54.140 --> 00:15:58.180
So most babies will
be ready to go a night

00:15:58.180 --> 00:16:00.280
stretch without
sleeping sometime

00:16:00.280 --> 00:16:02.290
between six and nine months.

00:16:02.290 --> 00:16:05.500
But that's something to speak
to the pediatrician about.

00:16:05.500 --> 00:16:09.760
And ask the doctor, is my
baby ready to sleep 10, 11, 12

00:16:09.760 --> 00:16:12.472
hours without a feed?

00:16:12.472 --> 00:16:14.680
That's something they should
be coordinating with you

00:16:14.680 --> 00:16:18.550
and really relating to in
terms of their growth chart

00:16:18.550 --> 00:16:20.800
and how they're gaining weight.

00:16:20.800 --> 00:16:22.720
And of course, there
are different methods

00:16:22.720 --> 00:16:26.140
of night weaning that
the doctor should

00:16:26.140 --> 00:16:30.100
be able to guide you about,
or your lactation consultant

00:16:30.100 --> 00:16:36.500
if [INAUDIBLE] And
then also figure out

00:16:36.500 --> 00:16:40.400
if my baby is feeding to
sleep, then obviously,

00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:43.610
we change that association
first at bedtime

00:16:43.610 --> 00:16:48.190
so that then throughout the
night, we can be consistent.

00:16:48.190 --> 00:16:50.740
So that word consistency.

00:16:50.740 --> 00:16:54.640
Being consistent about any type
of sleep association behavior

00:16:54.640 --> 00:16:57.670
is ultimately the most important
piece of changing things

00:16:57.670 --> 00:17:01.510
if you're in a
challenger problem.

00:17:01.510 --> 00:17:06.220
Because when a child
experiences inconsistency,

00:17:06.220 --> 00:17:07.900
it's going to create crying.

00:17:07.900 --> 00:17:09.710
It's just that simple.

00:17:09.710 --> 00:17:11.200
They don't understand our words.

00:17:11.200 --> 00:17:13.240
They understand our
behavior, right?

00:17:13.240 --> 00:17:16.119
So having consistent
behavior is what

00:17:16.119 --> 00:17:19.910
is going to get you
to the finish line.

00:17:19.910 --> 00:17:22.540
So ultimately,
what's inconsistent?

00:17:22.540 --> 00:17:26.890
Perfect example is
well, at bedtime, we

00:17:26.890 --> 00:17:30.550
have our last bottle, and
the nursery is really dark,

00:17:30.550 --> 00:17:35.710
and he usually just drifts
off, and then I transfer him.

00:17:35.710 --> 00:17:37.810
But he's 10 months
old, and I really

00:17:37.810 --> 00:17:40.310
don't think he needs
any food at night.

00:17:40.310 --> 00:17:42.490
So when he wakes up
around 12:00 or 1:00,

00:17:42.490 --> 00:17:45.040
I just go in and sort of
pat his back to sleep,

00:17:45.040 --> 00:17:47.740
and he goes back to
sleep pretty quickly.

00:17:47.740 --> 00:17:50.330
But then, of course, he wakes
up at 3 o'clock in the morning,

00:17:50.330 --> 00:17:54.360
and I just can't take it,
so I bring him into my bed.

00:17:54.360 --> 00:17:56.970
That's a perfect example
of inconsistent behavior

00:17:56.970 --> 00:18:02.190
because that child never knows
am I going to get fed to sleep?

00:18:02.190 --> 00:18:03.990
Is somebody just
going to pat my back?

00:18:03.990 --> 00:18:07.630
Or am I just going to
come into bed with them?

00:18:07.630 --> 00:18:11.610
So in some ways, having
one thing to undo is easier

00:18:11.610 --> 00:18:14.550
and ultimately, of course,
being consistent about having

00:18:14.550 --> 00:18:20.940
the baby fall asleep in their
crib is what we're looking for.

00:18:20.940 --> 00:18:23.010
Now in terms of methods, right?

00:18:23.010 --> 00:18:25.770
Because there are lots of
different books out there

00:18:25.770 --> 00:18:28.800
and lots of information
about how to change things.

00:18:28.800 --> 00:18:32.370
There's basically
three behavioral ways

00:18:32.370 --> 00:18:35.640
of changing a sleep challenge.

00:18:35.640 --> 00:18:41.280
There's extinction, which
is well known as cry it out.

00:18:41.280 --> 00:18:43.260
And that essentially
is the method

00:18:43.260 --> 00:18:48.420
of putting my child in
her crib at bedtime,

00:18:48.420 --> 00:18:51.600
I say good night, I
leave, and that's it

00:18:51.600 --> 00:18:55.590
until whatever time in
the morning you decide.

00:18:55.590 --> 00:18:59.550
That means no
checking, no nothing.

00:18:59.550 --> 00:19:01.140
And that's why we
call it cry it out.

00:19:01.140 --> 00:19:04.060
It does tend to be very popular.

00:19:04.060 --> 00:19:06.900
And if it works, it
works pretty quickly.

00:19:06.900 --> 00:19:10.750
It should work fairly quickly.

00:19:10.750 --> 00:19:15.150
The person who sort of
coined the methodology,

00:19:15.150 --> 00:19:19.210
Dr. Marc Weissbluth, has said it
doesn't work for all children.

00:19:19.210 --> 00:19:21.180
So if you find
yourself in a situation

00:19:21.180 --> 00:19:25.050
where it doesn't seem to be
getting better pretty quickly,

00:19:25.050 --> 00:19:30.420
you definitely want to
change tack and course.

00:19:30.420 --> 00:19:31.870
Next, time checks.

00:19:31.870 --> 00:19:35.700
Time checks are basically
graduated extinction

00:19:35.700 --> 00:19:39.570
and were really made popular
by Dr. Richard Ferber.

00:19:39.570 --> 00:19:45.720
So ferberizing, as many people
know it as, basically goes

00:19:45.720 --> 00:19:48.210
under the premise
of well, I'm going

00:19:48.210 --> 00:19:53.561
to give my child the space and
time to calm themselves down.

00:19:53.561 --> 00:19:54.060
Right?

00:19:54.060 --> 00:19:56.730
So I'm going to put
the child in the crib,

00:19:56.730 --> 00:20:00.630
leave, and then in
graduated time intervals,

00:20:00.630 --> 00:20:03.840
quickly check on the
child, but ultimately

00:20:03.840 --> 00:20:06.630
allow them to put
themselves to sleep.

00:20:06.630 --> 00:20:10.900
So that means going in graduated
intervals, let's say 5 minutes,

00:20:10.900 --> 00:20:15.090
10 minutes, 15 minutes
from the last check,

00:20:15.090 --> 00:20:16.680
not from the beginning.

00:20:16.680 --> 00:20:18.720
So you're not going
in every five minutes.

00:20:18.720 --> 00:20:21.780
You're extending
those intervals.

00:20:21.780 --> 00:20:23.220
And then lastly, feeding.

00:20:23.220 --> 00:20:25.830
And feeding really means--

00:20:25.830 --> 00:20:29.520
in some ways, I like to think
of it as a behavioral weaning.

00:20:29.520 --> 00:20:33.930
So we're doing less and less
to assist the child as he

00:20:33.930 --> 00:20:38.880
or she falls asleep and
then work our way away

00:20:38.880 --> 00:20:39.930
in physical space.

00:20:42.700 --> 00:20:47.130
So those are sort of the
most popular methodologies

00:20:47.130 --> 00:20:51.180
out there to have your
child get to sleep

00:20:51.180 --> 00:20:53.370
and sleep well
through the night.

00:20:53.370 --> 00:20:55.380
And again, as I said
before, I always

00:20:55.380 --> 00:20:58.650
want to encourage parents
to start at bedtime,

00:20:58.650 --> 00:21:02.130
work on night time, and
then work on naps last.

00:21:02.130 --> 00:21:06.840
It just tends to be the most
effective way for things

00:21:06.840 --> 00:21:12.780
to change efficiently
and most easily.

00:21:12.780 --> 00:21:14.900
And of course, if
all else fails,

00:21:14.900 --> 00:21:18.000
